FreezeTag is a free and open-source, self-hosted image management application designed for photographers, businesses, and anyone who wants granular control over how their photos are stored and organized. Unlike cloud-based solutions such as Google Photos or Apple Photos, FreezeTag runs entirely on hardware the user provides, such as a personal computer, a network-attached storage device, or any machine capable of running Docker. Self-hosting means that the user's data never leaves their own infrastructure, which matters for both privacy and cost. Cloud storage services charge recurring fees that scale with usage, whereas a self-hosted solution only requires hardware the user likely already owns. FreezeTag exposes its interface as a web application, so any device on the same network with a modern browser can connect to the same FreezeTag instance without needing any software installed on the client device.

FreezeTag was developed by a four-person team during the University of Utah's Kahlert School of Computing senior capstone sequence, spanning the Fall 2025 and Spring 2026 semesters. The team followed an Agile development process organized into two-week sprints, with regular standups, sprint retrospectives, and code review requirements enforced through GitLab. This thesis covers the design and architecture of FreezeTag, the engineering practices the team adopted, and my individual contributions as the frontend interface engineer, which included the core user interface implementation, a first-party plugin for displaying photo locations on an interactive map, and custom theme importing functionality. It also includes a reflection on what the experience taught me about building software collaboratively and about the challenges of designing interfaces for a highly extensible, locally-hosted application.